t%22%3A%22%3Cp%3EA%20new%20study%20by%20the%20Schmidt%20Heart%20Institute%20suggests%20women%20may%20experience%20greater%20long-term%20health%20benefits%20from%20regular%20physical%20activity%20compared%20to%20men%2C%20even%20with%20less%20exercise.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.jacc.org%2Fdoi%2F10.1016%2Fj.jacc.2023.12.019%5C%22%3Elong-term%20study%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20involving%20over%20400%2C000%20adults%20in%20the%20US%2C%20tracked%20participants'%20health%20data%20for%20over%20two%20decades%2C%20comparing%20physical%20activity%20levels%20with%20mortality%20rates.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20research%20revealed%20that%20women%20who%20engaged%20in%20some%20form%20of%20physical%20activity%20each%20week%2C%20regardless%20of%20intensity%20or%20duration%2C%20experienced%20a%20significant%20reduction%20in%20all-cause%20mortality%20risk%20(up%20to%2024%25)%20compared%20to%20inactive%20women.%20However%2C%20for%20men%2C%20achieving%20the%20same%20reduction%20required%20a%20higher%20level%20of%20activity.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20study%20suggests%20that%20men%20and%20women%20may%20require%20different%20levels%20of%20physical%20activity%20to%20experience%20the%20full%20health%20benefits%20of%20exercise.%20While%20male%20participants%20saw%20the%20greatest%20survival%20benefit%20after%20five%20hours%20of%20weekly%20cardio%2C%20women%20achieved%20similar%20results%20with%20just%20over%20two%20hours%20of%20moderate-to-vigorous%20cardio.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20authors%20of%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.jacc.org%2Fdoi%2F10.1016%2Fj.jacc.2023.12.019%5C%22%3Elatest%20study%3C%2Fa%3E%20write%2C%20%26quot%3BWhile%20the%20study%20highlights%20potential%20sex-based%20differences%20in%20exercise%20benefits%2C%20further%20research%20is%20needed%20to%20understand%20the%20underlying%20biological%20factors%20and%20establish%20tailored%20exercise%20recommendations%20for%20different%20populations.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BIn%20f